etymologies: late 16th century; earliest use found in William Langham (fl. 1597), doctor and herbalist. Origin unknown

definitions: A pimple, a pustule; a small boil. Now English regional (chiefly midlands).
(chiefly west midlands). An inflamed swelling on the edge of an eyelid; a sty.
A quaternary ammonium cation or salt, especially one used as a disinfectant, herbicide, or surfactant.

etymologies: late Middle English; earliest use found in Edward, Duke of York (fl. c1373–1415), magnate. From Middle French quatir, catir, coitir to hide (oneself), to crouch (used reflexively; 1200 in Old French), to hide, to fall to the ground, to beat (14th century; earliest with reference to the sound of a stork shutting its bill; compare also an apparently isolated use in sense ‘to thrust’; French catir to press, beat (in clothmaking and in gilding), French regional (northern and western) se catir, se coitir to hide oneself, to crouch), further etymology uncertain, perhaps ultimately from classical Latin coāctus compressed, compelled

definitions: To crouch down close to the ground, as an animal in hiding; to squat.
To beat or press down; to squash, flatten; to crush.
